{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512322","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512322"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:53:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:53:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11874"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11874"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.09,0.1,0.53,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4474"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48491"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4474"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11874"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33408"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"651"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2079"},{"type":"tags","id":"2254"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6544"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6847"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12671"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48491"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old man is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit following a motor-vehicle crash in which the air bags deployed and he sustained chest wall trauma and a severe head injury. He was intubated upon arrival to the Emergency Department due a GCS score of 6 and has been hyperventilated for the last hour. His arterial blood gas shows a pH of 7.52 (7.35 \u2013 7.45), PaCO2 of 30 mmHg (35 \u2013 45) and HCO3- of 23 mmol/L (18 \u2013 24). His most recent ECG shows ST segment depression, T-wave flattening and occasional premature ventricular contractions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the ECG features?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cardiac tamponade","Increased intracranial pressure","Metabolic alkalosis","Hypokalaemia","Type 2 respiratory failure"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG abnormalities associated with hypokalaemia include ST-segment depression, T-wave inversion, PR-interval prolongation and prominent U-waves. The clinical stem presents a case of respiratory alkalosis secondary to hyperventilation. Hyperventilation is a contentious strategy used in acute head injury to prevent hypercapnoea and raised intracranial pressure (ICP). An alkalosis can result in a shift of potassium intracellularly, thus reducing potassium concentration in the extracellular fluid and resulting in \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypokalaemia. \u003C/strong\u003EThis intracellular shift is accompanied by efflux of hydrogen and sodium ions to the extracellular space in an attempt to counter the effect of alkalosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetabolic alkalosis \u003C/strong\u003Ecan result in the ECG changes listed in the clinical vignette. However, the ABG findings are inconsistent with metabolic alkalosis as the HCO3- findings are within normal values (22-26 mmol/L).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased intracranial pressure \u003C/strong\u003Eis certainly something which would need to be considered given the stem refers to head injury. Increased intracranial pressure can result in ECG abnormalities, specifically widespread giant T-wave inversion (often referred to as \u0022cerebral T-waves\u0022), QT prolongation and bradycardia in severe cases (as part of the \u0027Cushing reflex\u0027 and indicates imminent brainstem herniation).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac tamponade \u003C/strong\u003Ecan result from penetrating injury or trauma to the chest wall. Tamponade will result in a form of obstructive shock and is associated with the ECG changes of tachycardia, low QRS voltage and electrical aternans (alternating QRS amplitude).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 respiratory failure \u003C/strong\u003Eis also known as hypercapnia (increased PaCO2) and results from insufficient ventilation and can be due to airflow obstruction, reduced respiratory system compliance, reduced respiratory drive, central respiratory failure or reduced muscle power due to neuromuscular disease. This is inconsistent with the ABG findings in stem which indicate a respiratory alkalosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Respiratory alkalosis can result in an intracellular shift of potassium and result in hypokalaemia.","ECG changes associated with hypokalaemia include ST-segment depression, T-wave inversion, PR-interval prolongation and prominent U-waves."],"references":["Brady WJ, Lipinski MJ et al. Electrocardiogram in Clinical Medicine. 1st edition, 2020","Wang X, Han D, Li G. Electrocardiographic manifestations in severe hypokalemia. J Int Med Res. 2020; 48: 0300060518811058.","Brain Trauma Foundation. (2016) Guidelines for the Management of Severe TBI, 4th Edition. https://braintrauma.org/coma/guidelines/guidelines-for-the-management-of-severe-tbi-4th-ed"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33408"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11874"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33408"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-12T18:34:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-12T18:34:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id"